>Not just any bike

My definition: Motivation is the urge to do something to reach a goal you want to reach. Making progress towards or reaching that goal should make you content, give you a sense of accomplishment and build up more motivation.

Yet to me, starting to work on stuff is extremely difficult.
It's like something is holding me back (I can pretty much feel it physically, despite it being a neurological/psychological thing), despite me knowing the consequences of not working on what I'm trying to start working on.
Similar are things I like or really want to do, like learning instruments, learning languages, playing games. For example, in 90% of the cases, starting a game I really like is "too much effort," because I have to "get into it again."
Or despite really wanting to be able to speak a specific language, I can't get myself to sit down and start learning. It has been like this forever.
Through the motivation of wanting to be able to speak that language, discipline should kick in or build up and make me sit down, but discipline doing its thing rarely happens for me.

Anonymous Tue 10 Aug 2021 10:02:19 No.40804033 Report
Quoted By: >>40804646
>>40803671
But discipline is something you have to build for yourself. It's not a huge boulder that's going to start rolling because of a small push provided by your motivation; it's a daily routine to sit down and work at a certain time, or in a certain way, even when you don't feel like doing it. It's a lot closer to working out - the more you do it, the easier it gets - than it is to getting a random burst of energy telling you to get started. If anything, when you come up with a new idea - whether a new project entirely or something to do with a current project - and you get excited to work with it, that's motivation. That will usually fade quickly, whereas disciple will keep you in your seat until the alarm goes off, telling you that your work session is over

On a side note, I've had periods where I've felt the same way about games. Turns out that it came down to that nagging feeling in the back of my head that kept telling me I had more important stuff to do, and I just wasn't able to relax and enjoy something because I know I was neglecting something else. I might be very different to you on that point, however

>>40804033
Yes, discipline can be built. Sometimes it's built indirectly (upbringing) or is inherent (based on individual interest in topics and/or progressing those; read: motivation) in my opinion.
But there's no use for discipline if all your efforts lead to no success at all.
Say, I have an hour each week dedicated to learning and each week, I sit down for this hour trying to focus only on that. During those 60 minutes, I have like 15 minutes I can manage to focus on learning at most (if I can manage to focus at all during that scheduled hour; in 90% of the cases, I can't), then there's no use in building or keeping up discipline or starting at all. It just breeds frustration, because you're hitting a wall or are failing again and again until you're finally lucky enough to progress a tiny bit at random every few weeks or months.
Do this for years and discipline becomes irrelevant at some point and it will kill motivation.
Also bear in mind that disorders like ADHD can have an effect on this and completely counter or even negate any effort you're making.

I'm trying to figure that out myself. Thankfully for me that only happens when I'm working on something I plan to post publicly.

In my opinion, an hour a week isn't enough to learn anything. And, yes, discipline is wasted if you're applying it to pointless endeavors. You'd be better off downloading Duolingo and spending 5 minutes a day learning, than trying to force yourself to pick up a week-old thread and continue where you left off. Your brain isn't designed to handle those kinds of gaps in a continuing flow of information - just try reading a book in the same way and you'll see what happens. If you really want to learn, an hour a day is probably your best best, and that's where discipline comes in. If you can't bring yourself to make time for something you want to do or learn, that just proves you were never serious about it, and, by the same coin, if you put in the time you will see results Frustration comes from lack of progress, not lack of discipline or motivation, and your effective 15 minutes a week is going to make it feel like you'll need several lifetimes to get anywhere - of course that's going to be demotivating. I think you should decide whether it's actually important to you, and then either let it go or actually act as if it's important

I'd also recommend this video on building effective habits (mileage may vary, etc.): https://youtu.be/vM39qhXle4g
